1. Top-20 bigram associations are dominated by tokenization artifacts (contractions
   split into two tokens: didn/t, wouldn/t, etc.) and proper name pairs (davy/byrne,
   paddy/leonard). Consider filtering out contraction fragments (tokens that are just
   "t" or "s" following an apostrophe split) and perhaps showing separate tables for
   name-bigrams vs. content-word bigrams so that thematic associations (food, body,
   Molly, memory) can surface in the top-20 list.

2. The minimum frequency threshold in associative_chains is set to 3 for unigram_freq[w1],
   but many of the top results still have counts of only 3. This means a bigram that
   appears 3 times out of 3 total occurrences of w1 gets P=1.0, which is not very
   informative. Consider raising the threshold (e.g., to 5 or 10) or using a pointwise
   mutual information (PMI) measure instead of raw conditional probability to surface
   more genuinely interesting collocations.

3. The cross-sentence transitions use random.sample with no fixed seed, so the "Sample
   Cross-Sentence Transitions" section produces different output on every run. Consider
   setting random.seed() at the top of main or before the sample call for reproducibility.

4. The trigram model generates very short output (often just one or two words, or even
   just a period). This is because MLE trigram models on small corpora quickly reach
   end-of-sentence padding tokens. Consider using a Laplace-smoothed model for generation
   as well, or increasing the number of generation attempts and filtering out degenerate
   (sub-3-word) sentences.

5. Exercise 2 uses Austen's Emma as the reference prose rather than a journalistic text
   as the exercise sheet specifies. The exercise asks for "a passage of journalistic prose
   from the Gutenberg corpus." Consider using a more journalistic/nonfiction text if one
   is available in the Gutenberg corpus, or note the substitution explicitly.

6. The perplexity computation in compute_perplexity passes the full output of
   padded_everygram_pipeline (which includes unigrams, bigrams, etc. up to order n)
   to model.perplexity(), but model.perplexity() expects a sequence of ngrams of
   exactly order n. Passing mixed-order ngrams may produce incorrect perplexity values.
   Verify that the perplexity values are correct by checking against a manual calculation
   on a small test case.
